Consider the two-body system shown in the figure. A wheel of mass $M$ has an outer radius $R$ and an inner radius $r$. The wheel is placed on an inclined plane with an inclination angle $\theta$. Its innermost radius is connected by a massless string, passing over a massless pulley, to a cylinder of mass $m$. The surface of the inclined plane is rough with a coefficient of friction $\mu$. If the system is in equilibrium, determine:
(a) the tension in the string expressed in terms of $M$, $m$, $R$, $r$, and $\theta$;
(b) the ratio between $m$ and $M$ expressed in terms of $R$, $r$, and $\theta$;
(c) the general condition for the system to remain at rest. This condition relates $R$, $r$, and $\theta$ to the coefficient of friction $\mu$.

