A spacecraft is sent to investigate a planet with mass $m_p$ and radius $r_p$. When the spacecraft is floating stationary in space at a distance of $5r_p$ from the planet's center of mass, it launches a tool package with speed $v_0$. The package has mass $m_1$, which is much lighter than the mass of the spacecraft. The package is launched at an elevation angle $\theta$ relative to the radial line connecting the planet's center of mass to the spacecraft. Determine:
(a) the angular momentum condition of the package with respect to the planet's center of mass;
(b) the speed of the package when it just grazes the planet's surface as a function of the angle $\theta$;
(c) the magnitude of the angle $\theta$ such that the package can just graze the planet's surface.

